, Sachsen, Germany":"Großrückerswalde, Kreis Marienberg, Sachsen, Duitsland","Chemnitz, Sachsen, Germany":"Chemnitz, Sachsen, Duitsland"},"en":{"1495–4Apr1570":"1495–4 April 1570","1491–1564":"1491–1564","1523–Male":"1523–Deceased","1525–1604":"1525–1604","1527–Male":"1527–Deceased","1528–Male":"1528–Deceased","1530–Male":"1530–Deceased","1495–1570":"1495–1570","4Apr1570":"4 April 1570","1495":"1495","1570":"1570","abt1528":"about 1528","12 August 1564":"12 August 1564","1491":"1491","1525":"1525","1523":"1523","1564":"1564","1530":"1530","1528":"1528","1527":"1527","1604":"1604","Grossrueckerswalde, Chemnitz, Saxony":"Großrückerswalde, Mittlerer Erzgebirgskreis, Saxony, Germany","Großrückerswalde, Marienberg, Chemnitz, Sachsen, Germany":"Großrückerswalde, Kreis Marienberg, Saxony, Germany","Chemnitz, Sachsen, Germany":"Chemnitz, Saxony, Germany","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gaertner","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Franz, Helmut, Kurt, Dieter, Erna, Ernst, Gerhard, Hans, Irmgard, Karl Heinz, Ulrich.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic) (<b>Gärtner</b>): see   Gartner  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Gartner","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Kurt, Gerda, Johann, Lorenz, Otto, Wolfgang, Bernd, Dieter, Frieda, Fritz, Gerhard.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic) (also <b>Gärtner</b>): occupational name for a gardener or vintner, from an agent derivative of Middle High German <i>garte</i> ‘enclosure, garden’. This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine) and in Slovenia (see 2 below). Compare   Gaertner   and   Gardner  .","Slovenian: of German origin (see 1 above). In North America, this surname may also be an altered form of the Slovenized variant <b>Gartnar</b>."]}]},{"name":"Jorg","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Dialectal (Alemannic and Swabian) form of   Georg ."],"variants":[{"name":"George","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Jorg Gaertner was born in 1495, in Großrückerswalde, Mittlerer Erzgebirgskreis, Saxony, Germany. She had at least 5 sons with Jorg Gaertner. She died on 4 April 1570, in her hometown, at the age of 75."},"et":{"1495–4Apr1570":"1495–4. aprill 1570","1491–1564":"1491–1564","1523–Male":"1523–Surnud","1525–1604":"1525–1604","1527–Male":"1527–Surnud","1528–Male":"1528–Surnud","1530–Male":"1530–Surnud","1495–1570":"1495–1570","4Apr1570":"4. aprill 1570","1495":"1495","1570":"1570","abt1528":"umbes 1528","12 August 1564":"12. august 1564","1491":"1491","1525":"1525","1523":"1523","1564":"1564","1530":"1530","1528":"1528","1527":"1527","1604":"1604","Grossrueckerswalde, Chemnitz, Saxony":"Großrückerswalde, Mittlerer Erzgebirgskreis, Sachsen, Saksamaa","Großrückerswalde, Marienberg, Chemnitz, Sachsen, Germany":"Großrückerswal